<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900823-0056</DOCNO><DOCID>900823-0056.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- American President Companies:   Concern Plans Cost Cutting,   Reorganization With Layoffs</HL><DATE>08/23/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13</SO><CO>   APS</CO><LP>   American President Companies Ltd., Oakland, Calif., saidit plans a cost-cutting and reorganization effort that willlead to layoffs and write-downs before the end of 1990.   The transportation and shipping concern said it didn't yetknow how many layoffs there would be or how the write-downsmight affect its financial results, which already are downthis year because of broad problems in the shipping business.American President had 4,994 employees at year end.</LP><TEXT>   The company said the process will take place in twophases, with the first focusing on eliminating &quot;non-essentialpositions&quot; and streamlining corporate organization. Thesecond phase of the program, which will last through 1991,will focus on increasing efficiency through investments innew equipment, better training programs and other methods.   A spokesman said the moves were in response to thecompany's &quot;poor&quot; earnings performance in 1989 and so far thisyear. The company has been hurt by a slowdown in the generaleconomy and by higher fuel prices, a problem that will onlyworsen with the current turmoil in the Middle East.   For the six months, American President had a loss of $1million, or 22 cents a share, on revenue of $1.1 billion.</TEXT></DOC>